   <text>
      <body><pb n="184"/>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>
            Rev. Samuel Furly</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>London</placeName><lb/><date when="1760-02-25">February 25, 1760</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Dear Sammy,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>At present I have but just time to tell you I hope to be at <placeName>Leeds</placeName>
            on <date when="1760-03-11">Tuesday, March 11</date>.</p>
         <!--1760 portion of date extrapulated from context-->
         <p>Your manner of proposing your objection puts me in mind of
            your friend <persName>Mr. Dodd</persName>. You speak <foreign rend="italic">ex cathedra</foreign>. 
            <note place="foot" n="1">Latin &apos;from the teaching office&apos;; 
               i.e., as if delivering a papal pronouncement.</note>
            But the matter is not so clear as it appears to you. It is, however, a point, 
            though considered long ago, worth considering again and again. But you must
            stay your stomach till you either see or hear again from,</p>
         <closer><!-- no closer exists, only the signature -->
            <signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>John Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
